FF MERGE VS NO FF MERGE

we have some trade of

1.no ff merge make history completed, and hard to understand
  but store it intact!
  linear history is easy to read, but he is not true history!

2.reverting and undoing merge
  is easy on no FF (because it has all history details)

Note: reverting commit (we will see on rewriting history section)
      is just new commit!
      that exactly opposite of last commit (do reverse each act on pre commit!)
      so in FF due to we move pointer, we have multiple commit that should be revert!
      but in NO FF we just revert merge commit!

                                                  main
                                                   |
                                                   v
+-----+     +-----+     +-----+     +-----+     +-----+
| C1  |<----| C2  |<----| C3  |<----|merge|<----| C6  |         //this is no ff
+-----+     +-----+     +-----+     +-----+     +-----+         //we just need rever merge commit
                          ^            |                        //but if we used ff merge
                          |            v                        //we need to revert both F1,F2
                       +-----+     +-----+
                       | F1  |<----| F2  |
                       +-----+     +-----+
                                     ^
                                     |
                                  feature

Note: we may have policy that we should always use no ff merge
      we could set it up on config file:
      "git config --global ff no"


SUMMARY: in ff merge, actually we don't use the other branch anymore
         we can delete it after merging!
         it move all commits on our current branch like they are exist always!
         so it remain linear and simple!

         in no ff merge, actually we store the other branch intact
         we just create some deviation
         so it make our history a little completed
         but store it exactly like what it was!